---
description: Keep tabs and add-ons split into dedicated files
alwaysApply: true
---

When updating this plugin:

1) Every top-level User Manager tab must have its own dedicated tab file.
   - Do not merge multiple top-level tabs into one renderer file.

2) The Add-ons tab is a special case:
   - Each add-on must live in its own dedicated file/class.
   - Keep `class-user-manager-tab-addons.php` as a lightweight orchestrator that composes add-on files.

3) For new add-ons:
   - Create a new add-on file instead of expanding an existing add-on file with unrelated features.

4) Avoid extremely large files:
   - Prefer smaller, focused files over monoliths.
   - If a file approaches ~800 lines (or clearly has multiple responsibilities), split it into dedicated modules/classes/traits.
   - Do not wait until a file becomes "very large" before refactoring; split incrementally as features are added.
   - Keep orchestration files lean and move feature-specific logic into purpose-named files.

